11:["$","h3",null,{"children":"Frequent Inspections (Daily/Pre-Shift)"}]
12:["$","p",null,{"children":["Required before each shift and during operation. Performed by the ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"operator"}],". Covers items that can change day-to-day:"]}]
13:["$","ul",null,{"children":[["$","li",null,{"children":"Control mechanisms for proper operation"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Wire rope for visible damage (section 1926.1413)"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Hydraulic system for leaks"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Safety devices (anti-two-block, load moment indicators)"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Tires, ground conditions, outrigger pads (for mobile cranes)"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Hooks and latches for deformation or cracks"}]]}]
14:["$","p",null,{"children":["Frequent inspections do not need to be documented per OSHA, but ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"we strongly recommend it"}],". When something goes wrong, the first question an investigator asks is \"Was the pre-shift inspection completed?\" An operator's verbal \"I checked it\" carries far less weight than a timestamped digital record."]}]
15:["$","h3",null,{"children":"Periodic Inspections (Monthly/Quarterly)"}]
16:["$","p",null,{"children":["Required at intervals established by a ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"qualified person"}]," based on the crane's usage, environment, and manufacturer recommendations. At minimum, monthly for cranes in regular service. Covers structural and mechanical items:"]}]
17:["$","ul",null,{"children":[["$","li",null,{"children":"Structural members for deformation, cracks, or corrosion"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Bolts, rivets, and other connections"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Sheaves, drums, and pins for wear"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Brake system components"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Electrical apparatus for malfunction or wear"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Chain drive sprockets and chain stretch"}]]}]
18:["$","p",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Periodic inspections must be documented."}]," Under OSHA 1926.1412(b), the employer must maintain a record of each periodic inspection, including the date of inspection, the name of the person who performed it, and the results."]}]
19:["$","h3",null,{"children":"Annual (Comprehensive) Inspections"}]
1a:["$","p",null,{"children":["This is the big one. At least once every 12 months, every crane must receive a thorough, comprehensive inspection covering ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"all items in both the frequent and periodic categories"}],", plus:"]}]
1b:["$","ul",null,{"children":[["$","li",null,{"children":"Complete structural inspection of the entire crane"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Wire rope (full inspection per 1926.1413, not just visual)"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"All safety devices tested for proper function"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Load-bearing components inspected for fatigue, cracks, and wear"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Hydraulic and pneumatic systems checked for integrity"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Electrical system and controls"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Foundation and support structure (for tower cranes)"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Boom, jib, and all structural connections"}]]}]
1c:["$","h2",null,{"children":"Who Can Perform Annual Inspections?"}]
1d:["$","p",null,{"children":["This is where companies make their most expensive mistake. Under OSHA 1926.1412(c), annual comprehensive inspections must be performed by a ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"qualified person"}],". That term has a specific legal definition:"]}]
1e:["$","blockquote",null,{"children":["$","p",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Qualified person:"}]," A person who, by possession of a recognized degree, certificate, or professional standing, or who by extensive knowledge, training, and experience, successfully demonstrated the ability to solve/resolve problems relating to the subject matter, the work, or the project. (29 CFR 1926.1401)"]}]}]
1f:["$","p",null,{"children":"This is a higher bar than a \"competent person.\" Your crane operator — even a very experienced one — is not automatically a qualified person for annual inspections. A qualified person typically has:"}]
20:["$","ul",null,{"children":[["$","li",null,{"children":"Engineering degree or manufacturer-specific training certification"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Third-party certification (e.g., NCCCO inspector certification)"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Extensive documented experience with the specific crane type"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Knowledge of applicable OSHA, ANSI, and manufacturer standards"}]]}]
21:["$","p",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Bottom line:"}]," If you can't clearly articulate why the person performing your annual inspection is \"qualified\" under the OSHA definition, you have a problem. Document their qualifications alongside the inspection report."]}]
22:["$","h2",null,{"children":"What Must Be Documented"}]
23:["$","p",null,{"children":"OSHA 1926.1412(c) requires that annual inspection records include at minimum:"}]
24:["$","ul",null,{"children":[["$","li",null,{"children":["$","strong",null,{"children":"Date of inspection"}]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Identity of the qualified person"}]," who performed it (including their qualifications)"]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Serial number or other identifier"}]," of the equipment inspected"]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Results of the inspection"}]," — including all deficiencies found and their severity"]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Corrective actions taken"}]," for any identified deficiencies"]}]]}]
25:["$","p",null,{"children":"ANSI B30 standards go further, recommending that documentation also include:"}]
26:["$","ul",null,{"children":[["$","li",null,{"children":"Photographs of deficiencies and conditions"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Measurements (wire rope diameter, hook throat opening, etc.)"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Load test results if performed"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Recommendations for repair or monitoring"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Comparison with previous inspection findings"}]]}]
27:["$","p",null,{"children":"The more detailed your documentation, the stronger your position during an OSHA audit or in litigation. \"Inspected — OK\" written on a piece of paper is technically documentation. It is also effectively worthless if challenged."}]
28:["$","h2",null,{"children":"Common Annual Inspection Findings"}]
29:["$","p",null,{"children":"Based on OSHA enforcement data and industry experience, these are the most frequently cited deficiencies found during annual inspections:"}]
2a:["$","h3",null,{"children":"1. Wire Rope Degradation"}]
2b:["$","p",null,{"children":"Wire rope issues are the #1 finding. Look for broken wires (OSHA 1926.1413 specifies exact thresholds), diameter reduction exceeding manufacturer limits, corrosion, bird-caging, kinks, and core protrusion. Measure and document — don't just eyeball it."}]
2c:["$","h3",null,{"children":"2. Safety Device Failures"}]
2d:["$","p",null,{"children":"Anti-two-block devices, load moment indicators, boom angle indicators, and limit switches that don't function properly. These are critical safety systems. Test every one during the annual — not just visual verification, but functional testing under controlled conditions."}]
2e:["$","h3",null,{"children":"3. Structural Cracks"}]
2f:["$","p",null,{"children":"Fatigue cracks in boom sections, turntable connections, and outrigger supports. These often require NDT (non-destructive testing) to detect. Annual inspections should include magnetic particle or ultrasonic testing of critical welds per manufacturer recommendations."}]
30:["$","h3",null,{"children":"4. Hydraulic System Deterioration"}]
31:["$","p",null,{"children":"Leaking cylinders, worn hoses, contaminated fluid, and check valves that don't hold. Hydraulic failure in a crane can be catastrophic. Document fluid condition, hose age, and cylinder drift testing."}]
32:["$","h3",null,{"children":"5. Missing or Illegible Documentation"}]
33:["$","p",null,{"children":"Load charts that are faded or missing. Capacity plates that don't match the crane's current configuration. Operator manuals not available in the cab. These are easy fixes but frequent citation triggers."}]
34:["$","h2",null,{"children":"The 12-Month Trap"}]
35:["$","p",null,{"children":"\"Annual\" means at intervals not exceeding 12 months. If your last annual was January 15, 2025, the next one must be completed by January 15, 2026. Not \"sometime in January.\" Not \"Q1 2026.\" Before the 12-month anniversary."}]
36:["$","p",null,{"children":"This sounds obvious until you manage a fleet of 20+ cranes, each with different inspection dates, plus equipment that gets added, transferred, or rented throughout the year. Without a tracking system, deadlines slip — and a single missed annual turns your entire compliance program into a liability."}]
37:["$","p",null,{"children":"If OSHA walks onto your site and asks for the annual inspection record on a specific crane, and it's 13 months old, you are in violation. Period. There's no grace period, no \"we were going to do it next week.\""}]
38:["$","h2",null,{"children":"Digital Tracking Changes Everything"}]
39:["$","p",null,{"children":"The companies that never miss an annual inspection aren't the ones with the best memories. They're the ones with systems that make missing impossible."}]
3a:["$","p",null,{"children":"A proper crane inspection management system should:"}]
3b:["$","ul",null,{"children":[["$","li",null,{"children":"Automatically calculate next-due dates for every crane in your fleet"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Send escalating alerts at 90, 60, 30, and 7 days before an annual is due"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Flag overdue inspections on a dashboard visible to safety directors"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Store the inspector's qualifications alongside the inspection record"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Generate audit-ready PDF reports that include all required data points"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Track corrective actions from finding through resolution"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Maintain a complete inspection history for every piece of equipment"}]]}]
3c:["$","p",null,{"children":"Paper binders and spreadsheets can technically meet the documentation requirement. But when you need to produce records for 15 cranes spanning 3 years during an OSHA investigation, the company with organized digital records spends 10 minutes. The company with paper binders spends 10 days — if they can find everything at all."}]
3d:["$","h2",null,{"children":"What Happens When You Miss an Annual"}]
3e:["$","p",null,{"children":"Missing an annual inspection creates cascading problems:"}]
3f:["$","ul",null,{"children":[["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"OSHA citation:"}]," Violation of 1926.1412(c) — typically a serious violation at $16,131 per instance"]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Equipment shutdown:"}]," An OSHA inspector can order the crane removed from service until inspected"]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Insurance exposure:"}]," Many insurance policies require compliance with OSHA standards. A missed annual could void coverage."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Contract violations:"}]," Most GC contracts require documented annual inspections. A gap can get you kicked off a jobsite."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Multiplied liability:"}]," If an accident occurs and the annual was overdue, every penalty and judgment increases substantially"]}]]}]
40:["$","h2",null,{"children":"Build a System That Doesn't Let You Miss"}]
41:["$","p",null,{"children":"Annual inspections aren't hard. They're just easy to forget — and expensive when you do. The solution isn't better memory. It's better systems."}]
